Abstract = {This article proposes the energy justice framework can benefit from a
   radical reframing to expose broader structural injustices in the
   transitions towards a net-zero energy system. There are two objectives
   of this paper: First, is to outline how energy justice can provide a
   radical critique of injustices of the energy system - a more activist
   centered approach; and second, to use energy justice to identify who is
   responsible for unjust policies within the energy system. The second
   point is important to understand what is meant by a `just transition.'
   Who decides how others are compensated for the transition and the loss
   of their jobs? The theoretical limitation of energy justice is the
