Month = {NOV},
Abstract = {In recent years, the concept of ``energy justice{''} has attracted much
   attention and research effort. Although all policy issues related to
   energy justice are worthy of further study, the time constraints posed
   by the looming threat of climate change suggests the need for
   coordinated policy research efforts. At the current stage of development
   of European societies, we consider that four policy research strands
   might be most important in the light of specific evolving trends of
   European energy systems. Therefore, we propose these priorities as a
   shared research agenda for academic and policy researchers. In this
   article, we develop and discuss the following four research priority
   strands: (a) intergenerational justice and energy justice, (b) justice
   and energy vulnerability, (c) transformation of the social imaginary and
   energy infrastructure, and (d) damage, compensation, and energy
   infrastructure. For each topic, we highlight their critical issues and
   research opportunities. We conclude that these priorities are necessary
   not only to accelerate the energy transition but also to avoid negative
   impacts that climate change and the transition phase could produce on
   already established patterns of inequality.},
