   the political spectrum. Such programmes are often premised upon the
   concept of ``just transitions{''}, which aims to reconcile environmental
   and social concerns in the movement towards a low-carbon future. I
   respond to some of the underlying tensions that underpin dominant
   discourses in this domain by foregrounding collective, disruptive, and
   non-capitalist forms of infrastructural transformation in the energy
