   that communities dependent on fossil fuel extraction and production for
   employment do not become `victims' of the decarbonisation process. This
   paper involves a theoretically and conceptually grounded comparative
   analysis of policy measures that have been introduced in three first
   world jurisdictions which have been dependent on coal for employment
   North Rhine-Westphalia in Germany, Alberta in Canada and Victoria in
