   politics, and alternative energy funding public opinion in the United
   States},
Journal = {ENERGY RESEARCH \& SOCIAL SCIENCE},
Year = {2021},
Volume = {73},
Month = {MAR},
Abstract = {Academic assessments typically conclude that right-wing authoritarian
   populism poses a significant political challenge to the advancement of
   climate change mitigation and adaptation policies. Right-wing
   recalcitrance and hostility to climate change policy have been
   attributed to the authoritarian personality, rejection of science,
   skeptical views of government elites and corporations, and even some
   forms of psychological distress. Employing public opinion data collected
   in the U.S. during the first term of the Trump Presidency, our work
   confirms that persons who score high on populism, authoritarianism,
   anti-science indices, and those who hold ideologically conservative
   views tend to oppose increased public investment in alternative energy.
   Not explored in the environmental policy and alternative energy
   literature is the conflicted (or compassionate) conservative; the
   individual who espouses conservative values yet supports social
   justice-promotive public policies. As an addition to current theoretical
   and empirical understanding, we find that conflicted conservatives,
   individuals who identify as politically conservative yet favor social
   justice expenditures, are significantly more supportive of enhanced
   public investment in alternative energy.},
